Visualizations unlock valuable insights and enable more effective exploration, analysis, and interpretation of data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Introduce the concept of distance between two vectors","timeRequired":"PT2M20S","description":"The concept of distance between two vectors allows you to quantify similarity, support nearest neighbor search, aid in clustering and classification, facilitate feature selection, optimize machine learning models, preprocess data, and enable geospatial analysis. Distance metrics provide a fundamental framework for understanding relationships and similarities within data points in various domains and applications."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Working with vectors","timeRequired":"PT51S","description":"Learn how to draw out vectors using Python and measure the distance between these vectors to quantify how similar two vectors are. Being able to quantify the distance between vectors is critical to understanding how different two concepts are and this is the essence of how vector databases filter and retrieve data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Working with vectors","timeRequired":"PT16M16S","description":"Learn how to draw out vectors using Python and measure the distance between these vectors to quantify how similar two vectors are. Being able to quantify the distance between vectors is critical to understanding how different two concepts are and this is the essence of how vector databases filter and retrieve data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Frame the query as a question or search","timeRequired":"PT1M56S","description":"Learn how to understand the data, formulate the question, represent the query as a vector, choose a similar measure, execute the search, interpret and refine the results, evaluate, and iterate. By following these steps, you can frame your query as a question or search in a vector database, leveraging the capabilities of the database to retrieve relevant vectors based on the similarity of their representations to your query."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Generate the question in machine-understandable language","timeRequired":"PT1M22S","description":"Learn how to generate a question in machine-understandable language for a vector database requires a combination of natural language processing (NLP) techniques and understanding the structure and content of the vector data. By combining an understanding of the vector data, employing similarity metrics, and utilizing NLP techniques, you can generate questions in machine-understandable language that align with the vector database structure and query objectives."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Adding data to a vector database","timeRequired":"PT9M48S","description":"Vector search in a vector database is important for efficient similarity matching, information retrieval, nearest neighbor search, multidimensional analysis, recommendation systems, machine learning applications, and real-time interactive applications. It empowers data-driven decision-making, facilitates personalized experiences, and enables efficient exploration and analysis of high-dimensional data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Performing semantic searches using Weaviate","timeRequired":"PT13M36S","description":"Returning the human-understandable version of the closest data points in a vector database promotes interpretability, contextual understanding, informed decision-making, validation, and trust, enhances user experience, and supports collaboration and communication. It enables users to effectively utilize and benefit from the retrieved results, leveraging their domain knowledge and expertise to make informed decisions or derive meaningful insights from the data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Vector search with Weaviate","timeRequired":"PT49S","description":"Learn how to perform vector search using Weaviate in Python. Going from a theoretical understanding of how vector databases work to a practical implementation is critical."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Vector Search with Weaviate","timeRequired":"PT11M5S","description":"Learn how to perform vector search using Weaviate in Python. Going from a theoretical understanding of how vector databases work to a practical implementation is critical."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Machine learning models and object classification","timeRequired":"PT2M2S","description":"A vector database understands your data through a process known as vectorization or data encoding. Vectorization involves converting your data into vector representations, where each vector captures the essential features or characteristics of the corresponding data point."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Translating data from human to machine-understandable","timeRequired":"PT2M11S","description":"Translating data from human-understandable to machine-understandable format is important for data processing, automation, integration, scalability, machine learning, and future-proofing. It enables efficient data analysis, interoperability, and integration across systems, facilitating automation, insights, and decision-making in a digital and data-driven era."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"ML models and vector embeddings","timeRequired":"PT15M52S","description":"ML models leverage the information captured in the embeddings to make predictions, perform similarity matching, or extract insights. The combination of ML models and vector embeddings enables effective data representation, transfer learning, generalization, and interpretability in various machine learning applications."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Search with images and text","timeRequired":"PT51S","description":"Learn how to build your own text-to-image and image-to-image search engine and even search over files on your computer using the Weaviate vector database. Vector databases aren't limited to text and can work equally well for images and in this video, discover how easy it can be to get this working."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Search with images and text","timeRequired":"PT14M28S","description":"Learn how to build your own text-to-image and image-to-image search engine and even search over files on your computer using the Weaviate vector database. Vector databases aren't limited to text and can work equally well for images and in this video, discover how easy it can be to get this working."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Scalability: When to use a vector DB","timeRequired":"PT2M43S","description":"Learn how to scalably use ML models in production to translate lots of data into vectors. Any data that your models can understand and translate, the more flexible the vector database becomes. ML models do not directly translate data into vectors themselves. Instead, they rely on feature extraction techniques and pre-processing steps to transform data into vector representations that can be used as input for the models."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Ways to measure performance of a vector DB","timeRequired":"PT2M26S","description":"You need to be able to efficiently and securely read, edit, insert, and delete both data objects as well as their vector representations—at billion and trillion object scales."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"CRUD operations in vector DBs","timeRequired":"PT9M58S","description":"You need to be able to search over these objects (filtered search) as well as their vectors (vector search) at scale within milliseconds."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: CRUD and performance","timeRequired":"PT55S","description":"Gain an appreciation of how scalable vector databases can be which also helps explain why large companies are leveraging them in production to power the search and recommendation over your products."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: CRUD and performance","timeRequired":"PT8M49S","description":"Gain an appreciation of how scalable vector databases can be which also helps explain why large companies are leveraging them in production to power the search and recommendation over your products."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Vector DB1: E-commerce RecSys","timeRequired":"PT9M15S","description":"Discover how vector databases can be used to build recommender systems to recommend items to a user depending on your personal preferences. This is one of the main applications of vector databases in industry."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Vector DB2: Hybrid search","timeRequired":"PT9M6S","description":"Explore the concept of keyword search and how this can be combined with vector search to perform what is called hybrid search. Hybrid search is a very practical technique used in industry to build reliable search engines."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Vector DB3: Retrieval augmented generation","timeRequired":"PT9M6S","description":"Explore the process of retrieval augmented generation and how vector databases can be used to improve large language models by giving them an external knowledge base that acts as long-term memory. This is the most popular application of vector databases in the industry and powers applications such as chatbots and agents."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Vector DBs","timeRequired":"PT1M","description":"Learn how to leverage large language models to answer questions retrieved from a vector database. Transformations are performed across all documents in a corpus and include operations such as removing non-text characters, citations, numbers, and punctuation. It can also mean converting all documents to plain text or converting all text to lowercase."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Stop words","timeRequired":"PT3M54S","description":"Stop words improve readability, but add nothing to the meaning of a phrase. Removing stop words focuses the statistical analysis on useful words, rather than words such as and, the, or is."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Stemming","timeRequired":"PT3M38S","description":"Stemming removes word suffixes and leaves the base word. Stemming applied to the word operations results in oper. This is also the result of stemming operating, operational, or operator. This results in focused statistics for the root word, rather than diffusing the result across all derivatives."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Lemmatization","timeRequired":"PT3M24S","description":"Lemmatization is like stemming, but uses a vocabulary and morphological analysis of words. If confronted with saw, stemming might return just s, whereas lemmatization would attempt to return either see or saw depending on whether the use of the token was as a verb or a noun."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Tokenization","timeRequired":"PT3M54S","description":"Tokenization converts a document to discrete parts, usually individual words. This is often referred to as a bag of words and allows analysis on the frequency of words, but sacrifices the context of those words. More sophisticated tokenization, such as phrase recognition, recognizes the difference between useful and not useful."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"N-grams","timeRequired":"PT6M32S","description":"N-grams are collections of two or more tokens, often thought of as phrases. The matrix elements are term frequencies."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create the document-term matrix","timeRequired":"PT5M29S","description":"NLP frameworks provide a method to transform texts into structured formats known as document-term matrices."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Weighting the document-term matrix","timeRequired":"PT3M56S","description":"Some NLP applications add weight to the frequencies in a DT matrix. Available weighting schemes eliminate multiple entries or emphasize unique terms rather than common terms."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Focus the document-term matrix","timeRequired":"PT4M13S","description":"Document-term matrices represent term frequency in a document. Finally, acquire a deeper understanding of how these mechanisms empower large language models to make contextually accurate predictions and translations."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"How does self-attention work?","timeRequired":"PT7M22S","description":"In this video, gain a basic understanding of how self-attention works. The hard part is largely also the part that doesn't change: text and speech recognition. AWS Lex allows you to create chatbots with various inputs and prompts while doing the heavy lifting for you. You can then focus on the logic."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"What you should know","timeRequired":"PT37S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Introduction to AWS Lex","timeRequired":"PT1M7S","description":"AWS Lex has a variety of concepts to learn. Bots are made up of intents that have slots. Slots have slot types and so on. It's vital to understand how to manage the inputs and outputs of bots by using intents and slots. These parts determine where the conversation is routed and gather user input."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS account and console","timeRequired":"PT52S","description":"Amazon Web Services (AWS) includes a significant number of services and features. Managing these services and knowing which services can be used and how can mean a difference in development time and cost. You need an AWS account to develop bots in Lex. Signing up is easy and many services are free."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Chatbot concepts","timeRequired":"PT1M48S","description":"With Lex, bots can be created with the Lex Console, the API, or your own custom process. The console can step you through the various pieces to help you understand how they fit together. It also uses IAM for access, they can use Lambdas and from there, anything goes! It's important to understand the concepts."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Lex API and CLI","timeRequired":"PT1M22S","description":"Using the Lex API allows you to use whatever client you like. A website can provide text conversations for users or a mobile app can allow for speech conversations or commands. The Command Line Interface (CLI) can also allow for quick development and management of the client side of your Lex development."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Lex Bot creation","timeRequired":"PT3M8S","description":"When creating a bot in AWS Lex, you can base it on an example or create a custom one. This allows you to not only learn from the examples but also provides sample bots for common functionality. The process also creates the needed IAM role for the bot. You mainly only need to provide a name and you're ready!"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Intents","timeRequired":"PT3M49S","description":"An intent represents an action the user wants to perform. It starts with a statement in text or speech from the user. Lex matches the request with the sample utterances of the bot's intents. Based on the match, the bot can execute a Lambda or collect input based on the slots. Then the intent launches the fulfillment."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Kicking off the conversation","timeRequired":"PT3M28S","description":"Sample utterances are what the bot uses to kick off the conversation. Each intent can have multiple sample utterances. They can be simple or complex. Lex uses these sample utterances and its built-in intelligence to make the best match possible. The more sample utterances, the more likely something will match."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Testing the bot","timeRequired":"PT2M2S","description":"Testing your bot can be done right from the console. When you're ready to test changes, you build your bot by pressing the Build button. Once the status is set to ready, you can test. The UI provides the ability to type text in or use the microphone for audio input. The responses will be returned in the same format."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: OrderDrink intent","timeRequired":"PT28S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: OrderDrink intent","timeRequired":"PT1M22S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Slot types","timeRequired":"PT2M6S","description":"AWS provides a handful of built-in slot types. These cover common data types such as numbers, dates, and location-related data. If your data is more generic than that, the alphanumeric slot type can be used."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Custom slot types","timeRequired":"PT2M37S","description":"Creating a custom slot type can still be based on a built-in slot type like alphanumeric. From there it can be given a name and be used in the intent."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"User input prompts","timeRequired":"PT4M16S","description":"A slot consists of a message to the user prompting them for input. The name of the slot is like a variable where the response is stored for use later in the intent."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Confirmation prompts","timeRequired":"PT2M58S","description":"Once the data is collected from the user, confirmation can request if the user wishes to continue. The slot values can be used in the prompt to clearly communicate what is being confirmed."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Create a restricted slot","timeRequired":"PT54S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Create a restricted slot","timeRequired":"PT3M22S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Closing response","timeRequired":"PT1M40S","description":"In responding to the user's request, there are a few options for the bot. A response message can be sent to the user. This message can contain the text defined in the console. It can also include various input data the user supplied when the bot prompted them for the slots. This is a text or speech portion of a response."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Prompting with card group","timeRequired":"PT2M37S","description":"A response card can also be used as part of the response to the user. Response cards are created if a response message was also created. It allows the bot to present the user with information such as a title, subtitle, and various buttons. The user has the option to select a button for their response."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Closing response for dessert","timeRequired":"PT1M19S","description":"As part of the response, the bot can wait for a reply from the user. This can be done with or without a response card. A response card can give the user various options but still allow for the waiting of a response outside of that, or it can simply wait for the response without the card."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Closing response for dessert","timeRequired":"PT2M33S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Versions and aliases","timeRequired":"PT1M52S","description":"To access a bot externally from the console, a version can be created. Aliases point to a specific version. That version can be changed as new versions are created. So a \"test\" alias can point to version 2 until it's ready to be released."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Client creation","timeRequired":"PT4M11S","description":"Various platforms can be used for client creation. For a JavaScript client, npm can be used to create a starting point template. Once created, npm can also run the local app in a browser."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Client preparation","timeRequired":"PT4M23S","description":"Access to AWS services is granted through various means such as API keys or Cognito. Creating an identity pool in Cognito allows for authenticated and unauthenticated users to have permissions. Adding the Lex permissions to an unauthenticated user can allow any user to access a bot."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Gathering configuration data","timeRequired":"PT2M14S","description":"The configuration for a local JavaScript client requires various AWS data. The identity pool ID needs to be provided. Also, various IDs need to be provided for the bot, alias, and region for the client to connect to the correct bot."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Testing the bot with text","timeRequired":"PT2M24S","description":"Amplify provides the packages necessary to connect to and communicate with a Lex bot. Once the interactions service is configured, the send command takes the bot name and input from the user to respond to."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Engage bot from CLI","timeRequired":"PT1M30S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Engage bot from CLI","timeRequired":"PT1M13S"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Lex and Lambdas","timeRequired":"PT2M48S","description":"AWS Lambda provides a great way to add functionality to your bot. This takes your bot from simple user prompting and input to true functionality. Lambdas can access a variety of other services in AWS like DynamoDB. Lambdas are serverless so they give you the best of functionality without the configuration and administration."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"BookTrip sample bot","timeRequired":"PT2M23S","description":"Bots can call Lambdas in various places to validate input and run functionality. Lambdas have access to many AWS services. Calling a Lambda from a bot for validation or processing can engage with services such as DynamoDB, SNS, and more."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Creating and connecting Lambdas","timeRequired":"PT2M36S","description":"Harnessing the power of AWS Lambdas from your Lex bot opens up a world of possibilities. Lambdas can do almost anything in server-side development including accessing other AWS services. A Lambda can read data from a database and write as well. If your bot calls a Lambda there is just about nothing it can't do."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Testing with Lambdas","timeRequired":"PT3M13S","description":"Once you've created your Lambdas for intent, you'll again want to test. This can also be done from the console UI or via your client. In either or both cases, you want to test the functionality with a variety of user inputs. The more complex your Lambda is, the more you want to test the possibilities."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Continue training your chatbots","timeRequired":"PT1M13S"}],"aggregateRating":{"@type":"AggregateRating","ratingCount":62,"ratingValue":4.8,"bestRating":5,"worstRating":1},"review":[{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Warona Mosiane","jobTitle":"Cloud Enthusiast|Certified Azure Administrator| Certified AWS Cloud Practitioner","url":"https://za.linkedin.com/in/warona-mosiane-54787851"},"reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":5},"reviewBody":"Enjoying the course, it's clear and precise. \n","datePublished":"2024-03-28T18:21:03.419Z","publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"LinkedIn"},"bestRating":5,"worstRating":1},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Javier Morales Barrios","jobTitle":"--","url":"https://mx.linkedin.com/in/javier-morales-barrios-349591295"},"reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":5},"reviewBody":"n/a","datePublished":"2023-10-10T22:08:07.189Z","publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"LinkedIn"},"bestRating":5,"worstRating":1}],"video":{"@type":"VideoObject","name":"Creating chatbots -
